        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>But are we throwing the baby out with the bathwater? What about Facebook’s ability to help us organize social movements? Have no fear. There was a time in the days of yore—before the early 2000s, to be precise—when people who wanted to do something did it face to face. In the last century, democracy did just fine without Facebook. Women’s suffrage, Irish independence, anti-Nazi resistance, Indian independence, a plethora of African independence movements, the civil rights and anti-war movements—to name a few—all succeeded sans Facebook. We’ll do just fine on our own.</p>
<p>I’ll keep my Facebook profile for now, but exclusively for posting columns, and only because I have to. But we should all put distance between Facebook and ourselves. We should heed the words of Confucius: “Wheresoever you go, go with all your heart.” Live life where it’s real. Live a life that goes on, even when the power goes out.</p>
<p><em>Tim Kowalczyk is a Trinity junior. His column runs on alternate Mondays.</em></p>

